<p class="article-lead">A fragrance brief should help a perfumer make choices. Replace abstract praise with boundaries: who will wear it, where, at what price and how it should feel beside competing products.</p><h2>The information that changes the scent</h2><p>Describe the target customer, market, use occasion, format and concentration direction. Name two or three desired scent territories and notes to avoid. References may explain brightness, sweetness, texture or dry-down, but should not request an identical copy.</p><h2>Define evaluation criteria</h2><p>State whether projection, intimacy, freshness or lasting dry-down matters most. Include packaging or color cues only when they communicate a real olfactory idea. After samples arrive, respond by code and time of wear; identify what must remain as well as what should change.</p><p>A one-page brief with clear priorities produces better development than a long mood board containing contradictory products.</p>
